Traffic evaluation of supermarket use in former Mervyn’s retail
As you know, it is proposed that the former Mervyn’s retail store located at
2480 Geer Road be converted for use as a supermarket. Per your request to
Inland Western who is the landlord, and on their behalf, this letter
constitutes a traffic evaluation of intersections near the Project site.
It is proposed that the existing and currently vacant approximately 61,275
square foot building, formerly occupied by a Mervyn’s retail store, be
converted for use as a supermarket (i.e. the “Project”). The Project
building is located in Turlock at the northeast corner of Geer Road and East
Tuolumne Road. The building is part of the “Mervyn’s Plaza,” which also
includes McDonald’s and 7-Eleven as outparcels, along with two smaller
retail buildings attached to the south. The Project site is bounded to the
north by West Minnesota Avenue and a commercial shopping center; to the
west by Geer Road; and single family residential exists to the immediate
south across Tuolumne Road and to the east behind the Project building
In accordance with the Turlock Zoning Code § 9-3-302, the property owner
is seeking approval of a Minor Discretionary Permit (MDP) to allow the
sale of food and beverages within the existing building, in order to market
the site to potential grocery store tenants.
The store will primarily focus on grocery sales, including dry groceries,
produce, dairy, bakery and fresh and frozen meats. The store may also
have a pharmacy and over the counter drug sales. Finally, the store may
have some general merchandise sales, including, but not limited to, paper
goods, pet food and supplies, infant and toddler goods, home cleaning and
care, cosmetics and automotive. Two (2) receiving docks and the
stockroom located at the rear of the store will support all sales areas.
A conceptual site plan is attached to this letter.

The first two intersections are controlled by traffic signals and the Project

Traffic counts were collected October 12, 2011 and October 19, 2011 at the
intersections when local schools were in session. Copies of the traffic
counts are attached to this letter.
The existing Mervyn’s building is vacant; therefore, the traffic counts do
not include traffic from the Mervyn’s store.

A trip is defined in Trip Generation as a single or one-directional vehicle

The proposed grocery use is most appropriately classified as Supermarket
(ITE Land Use 850). This use is characterized by ITE as being “free-
standing retail stores selling a complete assortment of food, food
preparations and wrapping materials and household cleaning items.
Supermarkets may also contain the following products and services:
ATMs, automobile supplies, bakeries, books and magazines, dry cleaning,
floral arrangements, greeting cards, limited-service banks, photo centers,
pharmacies and video rental areas. Some facilities may be open 24 hours a
In addition, the supermarket will attract a specific number of vehicle trips
that will already be on the road and will stop as they pass by the site as a
matter of convenience on their path to another destination. These are not
new vehicle trips but are considered to be pass-by trips. Pass-by trips were
calculated based on data published in ITE’s Trip Generation Handbook.
According to ITE, supermarkets attract a relatively high percentage of pass-
by trips in comparison to residential units which typically attract no pass-by
Internal trip making also occurs at multi-use developments such as between
the restaurants and the proposed supermarket. Internal trip making reduces
the number of new vehicle trips created on the surrounding street network.

The evaluation was completed using Highway Capacity Manual
methodology contained in SYNCHRO software. Level of Service D
or better is considered by the City as acceptable operation of intersections
Intersection levels of service were evaluated without and with the Project
under existing traffic levels and long-term 2030 traffic levels.
Table 1 summarizes the existing conditions analyses.

text.b: Table 1 – Existing Conditions Level of Service Results

page.text: As seen in Table 1, all intersections will operate at LOS D or better when
the Project is opened. However, the west approach of the project driveway
to Geer Road will operate at LOS E during the PM peak. This indicates
that although the overall intersection will operate at LOS A, vehicles will
experience modest delay when exiting the site during the evening peak.
Although an inconvenience, the delay is entirely on private property and
does not affect the operation of the public street.

text.b: ROADWAY SEGMENT LEVEL OF SERVICE RESULTS

page.text: Geer Road, Tuolumne Road, and Minnesota Avenue adjacent to the project
site were evaluated based on the volume-to-capacity (v/c) ratio for each
segment during the AM and PM peaks. Using v/c to determine LOS is
consistent with the Turlock General Plan. Peak hour volumes on the
segments from traffic counts and forecasts were compared with the
estimated segment capacities determined using the Planning Method of
Chapter 15 of the Highway Capacity Manual 2000. Table 3 summarizes
the results of the v/c evaluation.
Capacity for each road segment was calculated based on Highway Capacity Manual - Chapter 15 methodology.

text.b: Table 3 – Roadway Segment Levels of Service

page.text: As seen in the table, all road segments evaluated are expected to function at
acceptable levels of service. This is consistent with the intersection level of
service analyses which reported similar results. (Generally road segments
function as good, or better, than intersections since intersections often
function as “bottle necks” for network traffic flow.)
Intersection levels of service were evaluated for intersections and roadway
segments adjacent to the project site. Results indicate levels of service
expected at LOS D or better for opening day and year 2030 with the
addition of the project. No significant impacts are anticipated in
connection with the proposed supermarket project.
